---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-philippines', text: 'Leaving Philippine Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'ofw-considerations', text: 'OFW Considerations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Philippines SRRV Insurance', href: '/compare/best-insurance-for-philippines-srrv' },
  { title: 'Best Asia Insurance', href: '/best/asia-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Middle East Insurance', href: '/best/middle-east-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'service', header: 'Service' },
  { key: 'gulfNetwork', header: 'Gulf Network' },
  { key: 'phCoverage', header: 'PH Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', service: 'English 24/7', gulfNetwork: 'Strong', phCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$170/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', service: 'English 24/7', gulfNetwork: 'Excellent', phCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$190/mo' },
  { provider: 'Now Health', service: 'English/Asia focus', gulfNetwork: 'Good', phCoverage: 'Included', price: '$160/mo' },
  { provider: 'Pacific Cross', service: 'PH-based', gulfNetwork: 'Limited', phCoverage: 'Included', price: '$120/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', service: 'English 24/7', gulfNetwork: 'Good', phCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$175/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Filipino Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Filipino expats and OFWs. Find coverage for the Gulf, US, Singapore, and other destinations with English support."
  headline="Best Insurance for Filipino Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Millions of Filipinos work abroad as OFWs. Here's how to protect yourself in the Gulf, US, Singapore, and beyond—with options for every budget."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/filipino-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Filipino expats are among the world's largest overseas worker populations, concentrated in the Gulf states, US, Canada, Singapore, and Hong Kong. Your insurance needs depend heavily on your destination and whether your employer provides coverage. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Filipino expats. Strong networks in the Gulf, US, and Asia. English service 24/7, comprehensive coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent Gulf and US networks. Ideal for professionals in high-paying positions.</li>
    <li><strong>Now Health:</strong> Asia-focused with Philippines coverage included. Good value for those who visit home frequently.</li>
    <li><strong>Pacific Cross:</strong> Philippine-based insurer with international options. Budget-friendly with familiar service.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good global coverage at competitive prices. Strong European networks.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Check Employer Coverage First"
    description="Many OFW employers provide health insurance as part of the employment package. Check what your employer offers before purchasing individual coverage—you may need to supplement rather than replace."
    buttonText="Compare Supplemental Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-philippines">Leaving Philippine Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    The Philippine healthcare system includes PhilHealth (public) and private HMOs. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>PhilHealth</h3>
  <p>
    PhilHealth membership can be maintained while abroad. OFWs can register as Overseas Filipino Workers and continue contributions. This protects your PhilHealth benefits when you return and may provide some coverage in the Philippines during visits.
  </p>

  <p>
    However, PhilHealth provides no international coverage whatsoever. You cannot use PhilHealth in the UAE, Saudi Arabia, or anywhere else abroad.
  </p>

  <h3>Private HMOs</h3>
  <p>
    Philippine HMOs (Maxicare, Medicard, Intellicare) are designed for Philippine residents. International coverage is typically limited to 30-90 days of emergency treatment abroad. For long-term overseas work, you need dedicated international coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Maintaining Coverage for Family</h3>
  <p>
    Many OFWs maintain PhilHealth and/or private HMO coverage for family members remaining in the Philippines. This is separate from your personal international coverage.
  </p>

  <h2 id="ofw-considerations">OFW Considerations</h2>
  <p>
    Overseas Filipino Workers have specific insurance considerations:
  </p>

  <h3>Employer-Provided Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    Many Gulf employers provide health insurance as required by local law. UAE, Saudi Arabia, and other GCC countries mandate employer-sponsored insurance. However:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Coverage quality varies dramatically between employers</li>
    <li>Employer coverage often excludes pre-existing conditions</li>
    <li>Coverage may be basic with high out-of-pocket costs</li>
    <li>Coverage ends immediately when employment ends</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Supplementing Employer Coverage</h3>
  <p>
    If your employer coverage is basic, consider supplemental international insurance for:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Higher coverage limits</li>
    <li>Better hospital access</li>
    <li>Coverage during visits to Philippines</li>
    <li>Emergency evacuation</li>
    <li>Coverage between jobs</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>OWWA Membership</h3>
  <p>
    OWWA (Overseas Workers Welfare Administration) provides some insurance benefits for registered OFWs, including life insurance and disability coverage. However, health coverage is limited—don't rely on OWWA for comprehensive health insurance.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Between Jobs</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Employer coverage ends immediately when you leave a job. If you're between contracts, you have no coverage unless you've arranged your own insurance. Consider individual coverage that continues regardless of employment status.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global is our top recommendation for Filipino expats. They have strong networks in all major OFW destinations—the Gulf, US, Singapore, and Hong Kong. English service is available 24/7, and claims processing is efficient.
  </p>

  <p>
    Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited. Direct billing works at major hospitals in the Gulf, US, and Asia. Philippines coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Filipino expats who want reliable global coverage across multiple destinations.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with excellent Gulf and US networks. They're particularly strong in the UAE and Saudi Arabia, where many Filipino professionals work. Service quality is high.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pricing is higher than competitors but reflects premium coverage. Best for professionals in higher-paying positions who can afford comprehensive coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Filipino professionals in the Gulf or US who want top-tier coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Now Health</h3>
  <p>
    Now Health is Asia-focused, making them well-suited for Filipino expats. Philippines coverage is included automatically, which is valuable if you visit home frequently. Networks are strong throughout Asia and adequate globally.
  </p>

  <p>
    Pricing is competitive, and service understands Asian healthcare expectations.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Filipino expats who want Asia-focused coverage with automatic Philippines inclusion.
  </p>

  <h3>Pacific Cross</h3>
  <p>
    Pacific Cross is a Philippine-based insurer offering international products specifically for Filipinos abroad. Service is familiar, Philippines coverage is included, and pricing is budget-friendly.
  </p>

  <p>
    International networks are more limited than Cigna or Bupa, but adequate for many situations. Good option for budget-conscious OFWs.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Budget-conscious Filipino expats who want familiar Philippine service.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Your Options"
    description="Pricing varies significantly based on destination and coverage level. Get quotes from multiple providers to find the best value."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance needs vary by destination. Here's what Filipino expats should consider:
  </p>

  <h3>Gulf States (UAE, Saudi Arabia, Qatar, Kuwait)</h3>
  <p>
    Employer-provided insurance is mandatory but quality varies. Healthcare is generally good but expensive. Cigna and Bupa have the strongest Gulf networks. Consider supplemental coverage if employer insurance is basic.
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    US healthcare is extremely expensive—the most expensive in the world. Prioritize insurers with strong US networks and direct billing. California, Texas, and New York have large Filipino communities with many Filipino doctors.
  </p>

  <h3>Singapore</h3>
  <p>
    Excellent healthcare but expensive. Employers typically provide coverage for work pass holders. Foreign Domestic Workers have specific insurance requirements. Supplement if employer coverage is basic.
  </p>

  <h3>Hong Kong</h3>
  <p>
    Good healthcare with many Filipino domestic workers. Employers must provide insurance for domestic helpers. Coverage is often basic—supplemental insurance improves access to private healthcare.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I use PhilHealth abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. PhilHealth only covers care in the Philippines. Maintain your membership for visits home and when you return, but you need separate insurance abroad.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does my employer's insurance cover me fully?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Usually not completely. Employer coverage often has limits, exclusions, and gaps. Review your policy carefully and consider supplemental coverage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What if I change employers?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Employer coverage ends when employment ends. Having your own international policy ensures continuous coverage between jobs.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is OWWA insurance enough?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. OWWA provides limited benefits including life insurance, but comprehensive health coverage requires separate insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about coverage during vacation in PH?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Most international insurers offer Philippines as a coverage region. Now Health and Pacific Cross include it automatically. Check your policy details.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Which insurer is best for the Gulf?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Cigna and Bupa both have excellent Gulf networks. Bupa is more premium; Cigna offers good value. Both provide direct billing at major Gulf hospitals.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Filipino expats and OFWs need to carefully consider their insurance coverage. Employer-provided insurance may not be sufficient, and coverage gaps between jobs can leave you vulnerable. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for comprehensive coverage across all major OFW destinations.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage for those who can afford it. <strong>Now Health</strong> is ideal for Asia-focused expats, and <strong>Pacific Cross</strong> provides budget-friendly options with familiar Philippine service.
  </p>

  <p>
    Don't forget to maintain PhilHealth membership for your return, and consider coverage that includes the Philippines for visits home. Most importantly, understand what your employer provides—and supplement if it's not enough.
  </p>

</PageShell>
